":"","mother_name":"","interests":"5,22,6","bio":"A jurist, traditionist, theologian, a student of Aba Butain and a passionate follower and a propagandist of Ibn ‘Abd al-Wahhab’s revivalist movement. He would travel to Makkah, the centre of the Islamic world, and would often discuss theology with various scholars of the Muslim world. He managed to earn great respect from the Sharif of Makkah, who, at his encouragement, demolished all the domed-tombs in al-Mu’alla graveyard. His invaluable contributions include his two volume commentary on al-Nuniyah of Ibn al-Qayyim in theology.","children":"","siblings":"","spouses":"","teachers":"","students":"","kunya":""},"140046":{"id":140046,"short_name":"‘Abd al-Qadir b. Badran","full_name":"‘Abd al-Qadir b. Badran","arabic":"","rank":15,"birth_date":"","birth_place":"Damascus","death_date":"1346 AH","death_place":"Damascus","death_cause":"Natural","city":"Damascus","father_name":"","mother_name":"","interests":"9,5,6,22","bio":"A Damascan scholar in Fiqh, Usul al-Fiqh, theology, grammar, and a great enthusiast for Ibn ‘Abd al-Wahhab’s movement. He was initially a Shafi’i, and later, after much research and investigation decided to be a Hanbali. His invaluable contributions to the Madhab include: al-Madkhal ila Madhab al-Imam Ahmad, an all-round introduction to the Madhab; a commentary on Ibn al-Qayyim’s al-Nuniyah; a commentary on a Hanbali manual on Usul, Rawdhat al-Nadhir by Ibn Qudama, and many other works.","children":"","siblings":"","spouses":"","teachers":"","students":"","kunya":""},"140047":{"id":140047,"short_name":"Abu Bakr Khuqir","full_name":"Abu Bakr Khuqir","arabic":"","rank":15,"birth_date":"","birth_place":"","death_date":"1349 AH","death_place":"","death_cause":"Natural","city":"","father_name":"","mother_name":"","interests":"5,6,9","bio":"A prominent Hanbali scholar of Makkah, and a student of Ahmad b. ‘Isa. He was an outspoken propagandist of Ibn ‘Abd al-Wahhab’s movement, due to which he was imprisoned along with his sons, while the eldest of them died in prison. He was eventually released upon ‘Abd al-‘Aziz b. Su’ud’s conquest of Makkah, where he was, thereafter, appointed as a Mufti for Hanbalis. His contributions mainly comprised of works and rebuttals on theological issues.","children":"","siblings":"","spouses":"","teachers":"","students":"","kunya":""},"140048":{"id":140048,"short_name":"Ibrahim al-Duwaiyan","full_name":"Ibrahim al-Duwaiyan","arabic":"","rank":15,"birth_date":"","birth_place":"","death_date":"1353 AH","death_place":"","death_cause":"Natural","city":"","father_name":"","mother_name":"","interests":"5,6,19","bio":"A jurist, traditionist, genealogist and a judge in Qasim, most notably known for his commentary on Dalil al-Talib, called Manar al-Sabil.","children":"","siblings":"","spouses":"","teachers":"","students":"","kunya":""},"140049":{"id":140049,"short_name":"‘Abd al-Rahman b. Nasir al-Sa’di","full_name":"‘Abd al-Rahman b. Nasir al-Sa’di","arabic":"","rank":15,"birth_date":"","birth_place":"","death_date":"1376 AH","death_place":"","death_cause":"Natural","city":"","father_name":"","mother_name":"","interests":"1,5,6,14,22","bio":"A prominent jurist, exegete, grammarian with a great interest in poetry. He contributed many works in different subjects, the most of celebrated of them: Taysir al-Karim al-Mannan in exegesis; Manhaj al-Salikin a primer in Fiqh. His students include Muhammad b. Salih al-‘Uthaimin and ‘Abdullah b. ‘Aqil.","children":"","siblings":"","spouses":"","teachers":"","students":"","kunya":""},"140050":{"id":140050,"short_name":"Muhammad b. Ibrahim","full_name":"Muhammad b. Ibrahim","arabic":"","rank":15,"birth_date":"","birth_place":"","death_date":"1389 AH","death_place":"","death_cause":"Natural","city":"","father_name":"","mother_name":"","interests":"5,9,6","bio":"The Grand Mufti of Saudi Arabia, and a prominent Hanbali jurist. He played a leading role in the development of some important legal and educational institutes. His students include: Ibn Baz, Muhammad b. Abd al-Rahman al-Qasim and ‘Abd Allah b. Jibrin.","children":"","siblings":"","spouses":"","teachers":"","students":"","kunya":""},"140051":{"id":140051,"short_name":"‘Abd al-Rahman b. Qasim","full_name":"‘Abd al-Rahman b. Qasim","arabic":"","rank":15,"birth_date":"","birth_place":"","death_date":"1392 AH","death_place":"","death_cause":"Natural","city":"","father_name":"","mother_name":"","interests":"5,3,6,9","bio":"Prominent jurist, traditionist and a theologian, who is particularly esteemed for the most valued contribution to the Islamic heritage in this age, a 35-volume Majmu’ al-Fatawa of Ibn Taymiyah. His seven-volume commentary on al-Rawdh al-Murbi’ has also become considerably popular amongst the latter Hanbalis.","children":"","siblings":"","spouses":"","teachers":"","students":"","kunya":""}}